- Production polish vs. “warm” analog preference: Thriller’s “pristine high‑polish production” and heavily layered studio textures conflict with my stated dislike for glossy, over‑layered production that can reduce immediacy. While Thriller offers superb grooves and rhythmic variety, its pristine, multi‑layered studio sheen is closer to the kind of high‑gloss production I said I tend to avoid.
- Instrumentation and aesthetic: I explicitly mentioned a draw to older pop/Oldies textures (twangy guitars, slapback echo, upright bass, analog warmth). Thriller’s funk/disco‑pop palette (electric bass, layered synths, studio sheen) is less aligned with those vintage sonic preferences, even if its arrangements are tight.
