- Transient and dynamic preservation: I accept loud, radio‑ready mastering only when it preserves drum transients and vocal clarity. The synth candidate’s conspicuous multiband compression that flattens transients is a dealbreaker: flattened transients reduce the snap and rhythmic articulation I prize in groove‑first mixes. Turn It On Again’s low‑compression mastering preserves micro‑dynamics and transient detail, which better maintains drum snap and the interplay between bass and drums — essential to the “pocket” I favor.
